<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 94 / Major and Smith draw swords: Electoral campaign launched
with differences on economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GLASGOW, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The agenda for local government and European election campaigns was set out
yesterday as Mr John Major and Mr John Smith offered starkly differing views
of Britain's economic prospects.
Mr Major indicated that his hopes for an upturn in the government's fortunes
were pinned firmly on the strengthening economic recovery.
But Mr Smith told nearly 2,000 Labour activists at a rally in Glasgow that
Britain faced low growth, high taxes and unparalleled waste and corruption
under the 'crumbling' Conservative government.
The clash came as the prime minister made clear that he would not quit the
party leadership if - as widely expected - the Conservatives suffer heavy
losses in the council polls in May and the Strasbourg elections the
following month.
Labour received a boost last night with the release of an opinion poll
showing that a majority of voters no longer fears the prospect of a Labour
government.
The Gallup poll, published in today's Daily Telegraph, shows that more than
three-quarters of those questioned said they would welcome or would not mind
the election of a Labour government under Mr John Smith.
In previous periods when the government has been deeply unpopular, large
numbers of voters have remained wary of the prospect of a Labour government.
Separately yesterday, Mr Michael Heseltine, seen as a contender in any fight
for the succession, also moved to quell speculation over the Tory
leadership. The trade and industry secretary told BBC television that he had
'no doubt whatsoever' that Mr Major would win the next general election.
But there was still evidence of high-level tension between the Tory left and
right. Some ministers on the left were privately voicing considerable
satisfaction at the embarrassment suffered by Mr Michael Portillo, the
rightwing chief secretary to the Treasury, after his attack on public
standards abroad.
In an interview with The Sunday Times, Mr Major said Britain had the fastest
growing economy in Europe and the prospect of overcoming the inflationary
psychology of the past. 'If people want to talk generally about stewardship,
I am very happy to talk about the position the country is in,' he added.
Mr Smith told supporters a future Labour government would implement a
'business plan' focusing on investment, training and jobs 'to lift our
country out of the failures and disillusionment of the past 15 years'.
'We must invest in our country's future, and Labour's business plan for
Britain is, above all, an investment plan to make up for all these years of
Conservative neglect and decline.'
Mr Smith made clear that Labour's election campaigns will focus on taxation,
rising crime, and the alleged appointment of Conservative 'placemen' to
quangos responsible for 20 per cent of public spending.
Mr Smith also called for changes in the style of government, confirming that
allegations of 'Tory sleaze' will play a large part in the campaign.
The next Labour government would use 'all the resources and all the power of
government' to promote an economic revival.
Conservatives take Euro-sceptic line, Page 10
</TEXT>
