<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
What do the four main television channels offer for those who spend the
evening working and only become free at, say 11.30? Not very much. Today
BBC1 will give you two hours of Snooker starting at 11.40 with Alan McManus
playing Nigel Bond in the Masters Tournament. On BBC2 The Bestseller Brief
fills the Late Show's slot with a discussion from the US about 'the rise of
the legal thriller' (11.15 to 11.55). At midnight they switch to the Open
University.
ITV has another episode of the American action drama Magnum starting at
11.10. That is followed at midnight by The Little Picture Show with gravel
voiced Mariella Frostrup going through the new movies.
Then, between 1.00 and 2.20 there are two more American shows: Shannon's
Deal about lawyer/detective Jack Shannon and Beyond Reality (1.50) which,
today, is about tracking down a poltergeist.
Channel 4 begins a 100-minute documentary at 11.00, Soil Of Avellaneda about
remembering and forgetting in Argentina. That is followed by the ludicrous
Australian medical comedy Let The Blood Run Free (12.40).
