<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 94 / Bank backs fixed mortgages
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of England has made clear that it would like to see more UK
mortgages with fixed interest rates because this would make the operation of
monetary policy less costly to homeowners.
The Bank notes in an analysis of fixed and floating-rate finance in the UK
and abroad that the overwhelming majority of British mortgages are at
variable rates, in contrast to the practice in most developed industrialised
countries. It also notes that UK household mortgage debt relative to gross
domestic product is, at 60 per cent, higher than elsewhere.
This means mortgage borrowers in Britain can be subject to 'dramatic and
hard-to-predict variability in the proportion of income that needs to be
used to meet payment obligations'. Recent buyers, in particular, can suffer
'crippling' increases in outlays when the monetary authorities raise real
interest rates to counter inflationary pressures.
The Bank's observations, in an article released ahead of publication of its
Quarterly Bulletin tomorrow, will be familiar to many families which
suffered sharply higher mortgage repayments after base rates were raised
from 7.5 per cent in May 1988 to 15 per cent in October 1989.
The Bank concludes that the most important effect of more fixed-rate
mortgage debt on monetary policy would be a reduction in the sharp impact of
short-term interest rate rises on the cashflow of specific households and
corporations. 'This would allow interest rates to be increased quickly but
at lower cost - in terms of induced liquidity problems - to the private
sector.'
Half the mortgages granted by banks and building societies in the third
quarter of last year were at rates fixed for more than one year compared
with 17 per cent in the second quarter of 1992. But the Bank notes that
demand for this type of loan 'might evaporate' if money-market rates remain
stable for an extended period.
</TEXT>
