<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 94 / PIA seeks to reassure investors and potential members
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The draft prospectus in which the proposed Personal Investment Authority
sets out its stall is designed to reassure both investors and the firms it
intends to regulate.
Mr Joe Palmer, PIA chairman, calls the authority a new type of
self-regulating organisation, defining itself on the basis of the customer
rather than a category of product or advice.
Investors are told that they can look to the PIA for assurance that its
members will give them suitable advice and will not defraud them.
Potential members are told that the authority will take account of the
impact of regulation on the market, in terms of the benefit to consumers and
the burden on the industry, particularly small businesses.
How the PIA will operate: The prospectus defends the decision - which has
met considerable opposition in the financial services industry - that the
19-strong board should be made up of nine practitioners, nine
public-interest directors, including the chairman and the chief executive.
The Financial Services Act, it says, requires a self-regulating organisation
to have a 'proper balance' between industry interests and the public
interest.
The section also sets out the board's relatively streamlined committee
structure.
The industry will be involved in decision-taking through working groups and
task forces, and through staff secondments to the PIA.
Each proposal for new rules put to the board must be accompanied by a
compliance-costs assessment.
Costs and compensation: The PIA estimates its 1994-95 budget at Pounds
29.5m, including Pounds 5.5m in fees to the Securities and Investments
Board, the City's chief watchdog, and Pounds 1m for operating an ombudsman
and arbitration scheme.
The Pounds 6m set-up costs, incurred since spring 1992, are intended to be
written off over five years, adding Pounds 1.2m to first-year costs. But it
expects to raise Pounds 1.5m from other sources, taking total revenue needed
for the first year to Pounds 29.2m.
First-year fees for members will be about 20 per cent higher than their
1994-95 payments to existing regulators, in a flat increase across all
classes of member. The ways of calculating regulatory fees may be adjusted
after the first two years.
The PIA will have a cap of Pounds 100m for its liabilities under the
Investors' Compensation Scheme, which recompenses customers who cannot
obtain redress from the firms which advised them because they have gone into
default.
Maximum exposure for independent practitioners in any one year will be
Pounds 9.5m.
Joining: In looking at applications the authority will consider a range of
factors, including proof that the firm has appropriate professional
indemnity insurance cover and whether it is 'organised and motivated' to
comply with the rules.
The authority will be able to decide for itself whether to accept any firm.
It will also be able to give conditional acceptance.
Being a member: Members will comply with the training and competence
arrangements set by existing regulators. In the longer-term, the PIA may
impose higher standards.
All members must have a minimum of Pounds 10,000 capital, with higher
amounts set for larger firms and those which handle clients' money.
Monitoring will be linked to the admissions process. Information acquired
then will decide the firm's risk categorisation which will affect, for
example, how often it receives inspection visits.
In the short-term the PIA will maintain large sections of existing
rulebooks, but there will be new rules in 11 areas.
Service to investors: A 10 to 15-member consumer panel chaired by one of the
public-interest directors will be set up and consulted on
investor-protection proposals. It will produce an annual report on the PIA's
effectiveness.
If a complaint against a firm remains unsettled the customer will have the
right to go to an ombudsman, whose bureau will act independently.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
