<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 94 / British show little liking for work
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The British have the most negative attitudes to work to be found in Europe,
says the continent's most extensive survey of employee satisfaction.
However, a UK company, British Shoe, was one of the five best individual
companies in International Survey Research's annual survey, based on results
from more than 500 businesses.
The Swiss emerge as the most satisfied, and - Britain excepted - the
Protestant work ethic appears alive and well.
Employees in northern countries such as the Netherlands, Germany, Belgium
and Switzerland responded far more positively to their employment than those
in France, Spain and Italy.
Employees were asked to give their views on 17 aspects of working life
including company management, immediate supervision, training and
information, pay, job security and job satisfaction.
The Swiss came top in 16 categories out of 17 with an average positive
response of 70 per cent. The British had the least favourable attitudes in
10 categories out of 17 with an average mark of 54 per cent.
The overall satisfaction level of European employees remained constant
between 1992-93 and 1993-94, but this masked a number of changes. Attitudes
in the Netherlands, Belgium and Spain deteriorated markedly during the year,
although the Netherlands still came second and Belgium fourth.
Germany, which came third, saw a slight rise after a sharp decline in
1992-93. The 7 per cent improvement in attitudes towards product quality was
the strongest positive trend recorded for any country or category.
The categories attracting the lowest favourable responses were pay (42 per
cent) where France had the lowest figure of all, and communications (46 per
cent) where the UK was bottom. The categories attracting the most favourable
response were job satisfaction, working relationships and operating
efficiency.
The individual European companies which scored highest were Texas
Instruments, the semiconductor and electronics manufacturer; DHL, the
distribution company; and Nokia Mobile Phones.
Mr Roger Maitland of International Survey Research said it was useful for
individual companies to measure their employee response against a country
norm.
Employee Satisfaction: Tracking European Trends. International Survey
Research, Albany House, Petty France, London SW1H 9EE.
</TEXT>
<XX>
