<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 94 / New state secondary school opened in London
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
London's first new state secondary school for more than a decade has been
officially opened by Tower Hamlets Borough Council, John Authers writes.
Swanlea School (above) cost Pounds 9.55m and was built on derelict land near
Whitechapel Road.
It will take 210 pupils each year, most of them from ethnic minorities -
particularly Bangladeshis and Somalis. School signs are written in both
English and Bengali.
Swanlea's radical architecture, which features a broad central mall with an
arched glass ceiling and an integral sports hall, is designed to help reduce
the borough's truancy problem.
The architects hope that children will prefer the school's environment to
the streets of Whitechapel.
</TEXT>
