<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 94 / BAe to confirm Cahill will quit as chairman
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, BERNARD GRAY and JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Aerospace is expected to confirm early next week that Mr John
Cahill, its chairman for just 21 months, will leave the company in April.
It is thought that the company has prepared for Mr Cahill's departure as
executive chairman by seeking an outsider to become non-executive chairman.
The announcement has been delayed by negotiations over Mr Cahill's
compensation, which might be worth several million dollars. Mr Cahill
succeeded Sir Graham Day as chairman in April 1992 to serve a five-year term
on a salary of Dollars 800,000 (Pounds 533,300) a year, which for tax
reasons is paid in the US. He was also entitled to share options worth more
than Dollars 3m.
Pressure has been mounting on BAe to clarify the situation after speculation
that Mr Cahill would step down at the company's annual meeting in April.
Last night BAe would neither confirm nor deny the reports. However, it is
believed that BAe senior executives will meet this week to finalise details
of the succession.
Some BAe executives suggest tension had been mounting between Mr Cahill and
Mr Dick Evans, the group's chief executive. Mr Cahill, who was yesterday in
the US, where he lives, has been closely involved in BAe's unsuccessful
attempt to form a joint venture with Taiwan Aerospace for its regional jet
business.
The agreement last week to sell Rover to BMW for Pounds 800m largely
completes the company restructuring Mr Cahill set out to achieve.
BMW's relationship with Honda, the Japanese manufacturer that owns 20 per
cent of Rover may be clarified this week. BMW expects that senior executives
will within days arrange meetings with Honda.
Mr Nobuhiko Kawamoto, the Honda president, said in an interview with the
Financial Times that the company was open to a wide variety of three-way
relationships as long as Rover did not lose its identity as a British
company.
But expanding his remarks on the BBC's The Money Programme yesterday, he
said: 'If it becomes only a joint venture with BMW, and Rover thereby ceases
to be a British company, our co-operative relationship with Rover will not
last long.'
A BMW executive said: 'We do not expect complications with Honda.' Honda was
expected to retain its 20 per cent stake.
</TEXT>
