FT  05 FEB 94 / Financial Times Round the World Ski Expedition: Win a skiing
holiday in Courcheval or Verbier - Competition
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
In the second of our 'Round the World' competitions, simply answer three
questions below, and estimate how many miles Arnie Wilson will ski during
February. The winner will receive a four-day skiing holiday for two in
Courcheval or Verbier provided by FlexiSki, and two runners up will each
receive a case (6 bottles) of Singleton malt whisky.
QUESTIONS 1. What do double black diamonds on a US ski map mean?
a. Glacier b. Most Difficult Run c. Slalom Finish
2. Today we use wax - but what was commonly used on skis in Finland 1,500
years ago to make them go faster?
a. Tree Bark b. Animal Hides c. Leaves
3. Which country is hosting this year's Winter Olympics?
a. France b. Sweden c. Japan d. Norway
And how many miles will Arnie ski this month?
THE PRIZES
FlexiSki (tel: 071-352 0044) specialise in flexible breaks in Courcheval and
Verbier. Their prize features scheduled flights from Heathrow, private
transfers to a chalet, ski guiding and meals.
The Singleton is an award-winning Speyside malt whisky, made mellow by the
spring water from Dorie's Well and part-maturation in sherry casks.
HOW TO ENTER
Send your answers, plus your estimate of Arnie's mileage, with your name and
address on a postcard to: Round the World Competition, Marketing Department,
Financial Times, Number One Southwark Bridge, London SE1 9HL.
JANUARY COMPETITION: ANSWERS AND WINNERS
Answers: President Ford skied at Vail; Pistes are called Trails in the US;
the Four Hills is the famous ski jump competition. Winner: Mrs E Payne of
Petts Wood, Kent wins a week's holiday for 2 in Zermatt with Ski Scott Dunn.
Runners up:  David Blodgett of Voorheesville, New York, and Freddie Avis of
London W2, each receive a case of magnums of Mercier champagne.
