<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 94 / UN revises Somalia mandate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS, UN Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The UN Security Council last night approved a new mandate for UN operations
in Somalia emphasising peace-making and reconstruction after a turbulent
year in which the world body's peace-keeping capability was severely tested.
With the US and several other national contingents due to pull out by the
end of March,the unanimous resolution scales down the UN force to a maximum
of 22,000 troops, still some 6,000 more than Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, the
secretary-general, proposed.
He has asked about 40 countries to provide soldiers but few have come
forward, given the risks in Somalia, where the UN has suffered substantial
casualties and many Somalis have died in clashes with the UN force.
The resolution reaffirms that the UN must complete its mission by March 1995
regardless of Mr Boutros Ghali's fears about a resurgence of factional
fighting accompanied by renewed famine.
The revised mandate lays stress on UN help for national reconciliation,
including the laying down of arms, protection of ports andairfields to
facilitate humanitarian aid and reconstruction, reorganisation of the police
and courts, and the repatriation of refugees.
Also, the UN would promote 'the ongoing political process' aimed at
establishing a democratic government in a country that has long lacked
central authority.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>SOZ  Somalia, Africa.
