<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 94 / Tory anger at Portillo attack on foreign corruption
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Portillo, chief secretary to the Treasury, yesterday embroiled
the government in another embarrassing row after launching an attack on
corruption in foreign countries.
Speaking in Southampton, Mr Portillo contrasted the integrity and honesty of
public life in Britain with corruption and dishonesty overseas.
He quickly backed away from his remarks with an apology, saying he had made
a mistake in 'grossly exaggerating' the level of corruption in foreign
countries. He said his comments to students were designed to rebut the
allegation that Britain was descending into sleaze.
However, his remarks infuriated some Conservative backbenchers who
questioned the chief secretary's judgment in making a controversial speech a
day after the prime minister had called for party unity. Robert Hicks, a
pro-European, said: 'This is ridiculous. I wonder if he lives in the real
world. Where is the evidence in our community partners that such practises
exist.' A senior Tory MP said Mr Portillo's remarks were 'a severe
embarrassment to the government'.
In his comments to students, the chief secretary said: 'If any of you have
got an A level it is because you have worked at it; go to any other country
and when you have got an A level you have bought it.'
He went on to say: 'When you go into business you will win contracts because
you are good at what you do. Go to a number of other countries and you would
win contracts because your cousin was a minister or because you have lined
the pocket of some public official.'
His comments follow his recent speech lauding British institutions. Downing
Streetthen blocked a speech which would have emphasised the chief
secretary's Euro-sceptic credentials.
A spokesman at the German Embassy said: 'There is no question that our
students cheat. It is ridiculous to make such a comment.' A Japanese Embassy
spokesman said: 'We certainly do not buy our qualifications.'
