<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 94 / Finance package rescues Scots pit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Monkt onhall Mineworkers, the consortium operating a deep mine leased from
British Coal, has been rescued by Waverley Mining Finance, a quoted mining
finance house. Waverley has organised a financial restructuring involving
funds worth Pounds 7m.
The package should enable the mine to become profitable, and will allow a
second face to be opened at the Monktonhall pit, which is near Edinburgh.
The minehas had financial difficulties since it began production under the
miners' consortium in early 1993, after being closed by British Coal in
1987.
Thefinance house is understood to be taking 49 per cent of Monktonhall
Mineworkersby injecting about Pounds 300,000 of new equity and providing
about Pounds 1m in loans.
Waverley, on behalf of Monktonhall, has negotiated a subsidy of Pounds 1.8m
from the Department of Trade and Industry, while Lothian region is to
provide a grant of Pounds 230,000.
Bank of Scotland is believed to be writing off a substantial part of the
company's Pounds 1.8m debt and making available Pounds 400,000 of leasing
finance through its subsidiary Kellock. Trade creditors have agreed to the
restructuring.
Mr Willie McLucas, investment manager of Waverley, said the funding would
meet the need for Pounds 2m of equipment, Pounds 3m of short-term debt,
Pounds 1m to fund losses before the new production from the second face and
Pounds 1m of working capital.
The deal is to be formally approved by shareholders next week. In November
the miners rejected a bid for 100 per cent of the company fromRJB Mining, in
spite of the likelihood of bankruptcy without a rescue.
Mr McLucas is thought to have established a rapport with the miners which
should allow the deal to go ahead. He said: 'The mood of optimism and the
confidence that together we have created an exciting enterprise is most
encouraging.'
</TEXT>
