<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 94 / US shares slide after Fed pushes up interest rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Share prices plummeted in New York yesterday after the Federal Reserve
announced the first tightening in US monetary policy in five years, pushing
short-term interest rates higher.
When markets closed on Wall Street last night, the Dow Jones Industrial
Average was down 96.24at 3,871.42, a fall of 2.4 per cent, in spite of a ban
on computerised program trading introduced when the decline had exceeded 50
points.
It was the largest one-day fall in the Dow for more than two years.
Losses were particularly heavy in stocks of companies where earnings are
sensitive to interest rate movements, such as banks, utilities and
securities houses.
Investors sold stocks after Mr Alan Greenspan, the Fed's chairman, issued a
statement, saying the central bank's open market committee had unanimously
voted for 'a less accommodative stance in monetary policy in order to
sustain and enhance the economic expansion'.
The statement broke the Fed's practice of staying silent on policy changes.
In congressional testimony earlier this week, Mr Greenspan had foreshadowed
a tightening but left timing in doubt.
His statement yesterday was issued 'so as to avoid any misunderstanding of
the committee's purposes, given the fact that this is the first firming of
reserve market conditions by the committee since early 1989'.
Mr Lyle Gramley, a former governor at the Fed and now chief economist at the
Mortgage Bankers Association, said that the Fed seemed to have adopted 'a
new policy' of openness.
The fall in share prices reflectedinvestor concern that rising interest
rates would slow the economy and possiblybring to an end the long bull run
in equity markets.
The timing of the interest rate increase surprised world financial markets.
It is not expected, however, that European interest rates will move higher
in the wake of the Fed's move.
In London last night, where share prices were also hit in late trading by
the Fed's statement, some analysts were still holding out hope of an
earlycut in bank base rates from 5.5 per cent.
The US Treasury market also reacted badly to the rate rise, which the Fed
achieved through a modest increase in pressure on banking reserve positions.
This increased the federal funds rate, the rate at which banks lend to each
other, by a quarter point to 3 1/4 per cent. The benchmark 30-year
government bond finished down  17/32 at 98 21/32 , yielding 6.346 per cent.
On the foreign exchange markets, the dollar strengthened in the expectation
that higher US interest rates would attract money into dollar assets.
In late trading in New York, the US currency had risen almost 2 pfennigs
against the D-Mark to DM1.760, and more than a yen to Y109.30.
Unlikethe markets, Wall Street economists were pleased at the action. Mr
John Lipsky,chief economist at Salomon Brothers, said: 'They have
underscored their seriousness about controlling inflationary pressures by
acting in advance of market expectations.'
The Clinton administration took a relaxed view of the move. Ms Laura Tyson,
head of the president's council of economic advisers, said that a modest
increase in short-term rates was consistent with a projected 3 per cent
economic growth for this year. The administration has been pressing other
industrialised nations to relax monetary policy so as to stimulate economic
growth.
There was no immediate expectation in Washington of a policy change in the
light of the Fed's modest tightening, which still leaves US short-term rates
low by international standards.
US jobs growth slows, Page 3
Editorial Comment, Page 6
Currencies, Page 11
London stocks, Page 13
World stocks, Page 19
Lex, Page 22
Markets, Weekend II
</TEXT>
