<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Heavy selling in the derivatives market saw the futures contract on the
FT-SE 100 Index record exceptionally high turnover and drag the underlying
market down yesterday, writes Joel Kibazo.
Dealers had expected the previous day's strong performance to continue after
March opened at 3,543 and early demand by locals soon had the contract
moving ahead.
However, the release of disappointing German monetary figures brought a
turnaround in March after the first hour, and an announcement shortly
afterwards that there would be no press meeting following the Bundesbank
Council meeting triggered the day's strong selling.
Confirmation that there would be no German interest rate reduction only
served to increase the general profit-taking by market participants and was
in part responsible for pulling the underlying cash market lower.
The March future traded at a discount to cash for most of the session and
finished the day at 3,494, down 36 from its previous close and around 2
points ahead of its fair value premium to cash which now stands at zero.
Volume was again heavy, reaching 20,757 lots by the official close.
Turnover in the traded options fell to 41,397 contracts from Wednesday's
total of 54,902. Volume in the FT-SE 100 option was steady at 17,935, but
the Euro FT-SE option was well down, seeing a mere 1,018 lots dealt. Hanson
was the busiest stock option at 2,287 contracts, followed by Lonrho at
2,258.
</TEXT>
